The other thing I
would offer is that we

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:21.490
talk about cyber attacks.

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:23.100
We use the language of medicine.

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:24.950
We talk about
computer infections.

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:25.990
We talk about viruses.

00:10:25.990 --> 00:10:28.610
We use the language of medicine
to describe the problem.

00:10:28.610 --> 00:10:32.050
But we don't use the tools of
medicine to solve the problem.

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:35.630
What could epidemiology
bring to the table, right?

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:38.120
What would a World Health
Organization for cyber

00:10:38.120 --> 00:10:39.010
look like?

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:41.510
Public health models,
epidemiological models I think

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:43.450
could go a long way
in terms of helping

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:44.820
to protect the internet.

00:10:44.820 --> 00:10:47.570
And by the way, what could
we learn from bio-mimicry?

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:49.230
Right, nature for
four billion years

00:10:49.230 --> 00:10:51.890
has been building immune
system's, resilient systems.

00:10:51.890 --> 00:10:55.150
How could we learn
from biology and nature

00:10:55.150 --> 00:10:56.700
to drive this forward?

00:10:56.700 --> 00:10:58.800
Another big challenge is
human centered design.

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:01.800
Anybody every use like a
Norton Utilities product.

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:04.240
When my mom uses her
software firewall,

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:09.570
it says warning, error, MSCX
DL3 DLL error at line code this.

00:11:09.570 --> 00:11:11.620
Do you wish to proceed?

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:13.140
That is not helpful to my mom.

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:14.960
It's not helpful to me.

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:17.455
OK, think about all
the beautiful products

00:11:17.455 --> 00:11:18.330
we have in the world.

00:11:18.330 --> 00:11:20.850
A Leica camera, a Porsche 911.

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:22.710
Whatever those
beautiful things are,

00:11:22.710 --> 00:11:24.740
where's the Johnny
Ives of security?

00:11:24.740 --> 00:11:27.170
The guy that's going to design
the most beautiful, human

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:29.600
centered design for security.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:30.440
We don't have that.

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:32.300
And so because of
poor engineering

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:33.890
and a lack of designed
thinking, we're

00:11:33.890 --> 00:11:36.630
driving people to make
poor security decisions.

00:11:36.630 --> 00:11:37.832
We need to fix that.

00:11:37.832 --> 00:11:39.540
And I also think that
we need a Manhattan

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:41.270
Project for cyber security.

00:11:41.270 --> 00:11:45.220
We need to get really, really,
really intentional about this.

00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:46.760
And we are not at all.

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:48.850
I think you guys about
the XPRIZE Foundation?

00:11:48.850 --> 00:11:50.370
Just a couple miles from here.

00:11:50.370 --> 00:11:52.360
I'm working with them
to launch a $20 million

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:56.150
cyber XPRIZE for cyber security.

00:11:56.150 --> 00:11:57.990
Whether it's a
10-year-old kid in Chennai

00:11:57.990 --> 00:12:00.590
that's got the answer or an
80-year-old woman in Montreal,

00:12:00.590 --> 00:12:01.510
I don't care.

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:04.310
We need to build more
resilient and redundant systems

00:12:04.310 --> 00:12:05.350
to protect us.

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:08.250
The good news is, just to
put it all in perspective,

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:09.500
we can fix this.

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:12.210
Right, President Kennedy
said in the 1960s,

00:12:12.210 --> 00:12:15.520
before this decade is out, we're
going to put a man on the moon.

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:19.540
We did that, with way worse tech
then we have available today.

00:12:19.540 --> 00:12:22.280
If we could solve that
problem, surely we

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:24.500
could solve this cyber
security problem.

00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:28.020
And we need to, because
technology is awesome.

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:30.970
And it's going to bring billions
of people out of poverty.

00:12:30.970 --> 00:12:32.510
It's going to
radically extend life.

00:12:32.510 --> 00:12:34.093
It's going to reduce
infant mortality.

00:12:34.093 --> 00:12:37.490
It's going to educate millions
of people they never had access

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:39.090
to education previously.

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:41.700
But in order to achieve
that better future,

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:43.880
we're going to get
really intentional

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:47.200
about protecting against
these exponential undersides.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:48.861
The downside of technology.

00:12:48.861 --> 00:12:50.860
And that's what I'm hoping
to do with this book,

00:12:50.860 --> 00:12:52.842
and I hope you guys will
join me in that fight.

00:12:52.842 --> 00:12:53.800
Thank you so very much.

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:57.150
[APPLAUSE]

